{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-05","name":"Sir Christopher Seton of Seton","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Sir Christopher Seton of Seton","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Prefix","value":"Sir"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Christopher"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Seton"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"of Seton"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"alternateName":"The Good Sir Chrystell","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1278–1306","fullLifespan":"about 1278–1306","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/jmrcm/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"memoryArtifacts":[{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-88989-5089-17/dist.png?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/80525050","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-88989-5089-17/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-904-88989-5089-17/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","@type":"ImageObject"},{"memoryType":"STORY","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-101082-2195-28/dist.txt?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/111706312","headline":"Knights Templar Connection","description":"source:  http://www2.thesetonfamily.com:8080/gallery/The_Seton_Knights_Templar.htm\n\nThe Scottish Order of the Knights Templar was one of Royal appointment, an Honour presented to select individuals by …","@type":"MediaObject"},{"memoryType":"STORY","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7774-103055-9686-5/dist.txt?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/115836482","headline":"BIO","description":"BIO:  from http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SCOTTISH%20NOBILITY%20UNTITLED.htm#ChristopherSetondied1306\n\nCHRISTOPHER Seton (-hanged [Oct] 1306).  \"Cristofor son and heir of John de Seton\" did homage fo …","@type":"MediaObject"},{"memoryType":"PHOTO","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7734-115178-3724-0/dist.png?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/143720402","thumbnailUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-7734-115178-3724-0/thumb200s.jpg?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","deepZoomUrl":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/deepzoomcloud/dzpatron/v1/TH-7734-115178-3724-0/scale?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","@type":"ImageObject"}],"popularStory":{"memoryType":"STORY","url":"https://sg30p0.familysearch.org/service/records/storage/dascloud/patron/v2/TH-904-101082-2195-28/dist.txt?ctx=ArtCtxPublic","memoryUrl":"https://www.familysearch.org/photos/artifacts/111706312","headline":"Knights Templar Connection","description":"source:  http://www2.thesetonfamily.com:8080/gallery/The_Seton_Knights_Templar.htm\n\nThe Scottish Order of the Knights Templar was one of Royal appointment, an Honour presented to select individuals by …","@type":"MediaObject"},"birthDate":"+1278","deathDate":"+1306","deathPlace":{"address":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","geo":{"latitude":55.9623,"longitude":-2.9393,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"burialDate":"+1306","burialPlace":{"address":"Scotland","geo":{"latitude":56.81674,"longitude":-4.18396,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Sir Christopher Seton (1278–1306), also known as Christopher de Seton, was a 13th-century noble, who held lands in England and Scotland. He was a supporter of Robert the Bruce and obtained Robert's sister's hand in marriage. Present during the killing of John Comyn, Lord of Badenoch at Greyfriars Church, Dumfries, he also killed Sir Robert Comyn, who had rushed to Badenoch's aid. Seton was captured at Loch Doon Castle and executed at Dumfries in 1306.\n\nChristopher Seton was the eldest son of Sir John de Seton of Skelton, Cumberland and Erminia Lascelles. His brothers were John and Humphrey de Seton. This branch of the Seton family had long served the Bruces in Yorkshire, Cumberland and Scotland. (No connection has as yet been discovered to Alexander Seton, Governor of Berwick; however, it is claimed that Alexander was his grandson.)\n\nIn 1301, at the age of twenty-three, Christopher married Robert de Brus's sister Christina Bruce.\n\nSeton was present on 10 February 1306 when Sir John Comyn of Badenoch was stabbed by Robert de Brus in Greyfriars Church, Dumfries.[1] As Sir Robert Comyn rushed to aid his nephew, Seton struck him down with a blow to the head.[2][3] A letter of excommunication was issued naming the Earl of Carrick and three other knights, Sir Alexander Lindsay, Sir Christopher and his brother John Seton as John Comyn's murderers.\n\nSeton was also present at the coronation of his brother in-law King Robert I, King of Scots, at Scone on 25–26 March 1306.[1] Some accounts have him present at the Battle of Methven on 19 June 1306[4] but Duncan places him at Loch Doon Castle, an important castle for the Earls of Carrick and one of three that Robert tried to hang on to, but Loch Doon fell about 14 August.\n\nLoch Doon Castle, Ayrshire, was besieged by the English and after the surrender of that castle by the Governor Sir Gilbert de Carrick, Christopher was hanged, drawn and quartered at Dumfries in accordance with Edward I's policy of giving no quarter to Scottish prisoners. His Cumberland estates, with the exception of his mother's dower, were given to Sir Robert de Clifford. A small chapel was raised by his wife Christina, at Dumfries to the memory of her husband in 1326.\n\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Seton","sourceList":[{"title":"Legacy NFS Source: Sir Christopher Seton (3) - Published information: military-service: 19 June 