:"Overleden","1349":"1349","Abt 1295":"circa 1295","1357":"1357","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1222":"1222","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","about 1278":"circa 1278","1250":"1250","1306":"1306","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","England":"England","Scotland":"Schotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1278–1306":"about 1278–1306","1278–1306":"1278–1306","1250–1357":"1250–1357","1275–1349":"1275–1349","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1222–1299":"1222–1299","–Female":"Deceased","1349":"1349","Abt 1295":"about 1295","1357":"1357","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1222":"1222","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","about 1278":"about 1278","1250":"1250","1306":"1306","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Seton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Midlothian) and English: variant of   Seaton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Seaton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Seaton, such as those in Cumberland, Devon, Durham, Leicestershire, Northumberland, Rutland, East Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire, most of which derive from Old English <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea, lake’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though the Leicestershire placename probably arises from an Old English personal name <i>Sǣga</i> or a stream-name <i>Sǣge</i> (from Old English <i>sǣge</i> ‘slow moving’; compare   Seabrook  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Seton (East Lothian), from Old English <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Christopher Seton of Seton was born about 1278 as the son of Sir John de Seton of Skelton, Cumberland and Arminia Lascelles. He married Lady Christina De Brus in 1301, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1306, in Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, at the age of 29, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1278–1306":"umbes 1278–1306","1278–1306":"1278–1306","1250–1357":"1250–1357","1275–1349":"1275–1349","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1222–1299":"1222–1299","–Female":"Surnud","1349":"1349","Abt 1295":"umbes 1295","1357":"1357","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1222":"1222","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","about 1278":"umbes 1278","1250":"1250","1306":"1306","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","Seton, East Lothian, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1278–1306":"noin 1278–1306","1278–1306":"1278–1306","1250–1357":"1250–1357","1275–1349":"1275–1349","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1222–1299":"1222–1299","–Female":"Kuollut","1349":"1349","Abt 1295":"noin 1295","1357":"1357","1301":"1301","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1222":"1222","1275":"1275","1295":"1295","about 1278":"noin 1278","1250":"1250","1306":"1306","Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Seton, Haddingtonshire, Scotla